It's not as presumptuous as you might think (it's still fairly presumptuous). The more interesting chemistry you need for anything even approaching life has to wait for heavier elements to be produced in stars and supernovae. High-metallicity star systems only started appearing about 10 billion years ago, but they're still only about ten percent of the metallicity of our own solar system (about 5 billion years old), which might be too bare for much to happen. Planets formed very much earlier than Earth get steadily less likely to be capable of producing life, so while we might not be alone or unique, any aliens that do exist are far more likely to be our peer species or juniors than they are to be ancient precursors.

It's interesting in the context of explaining the Fermi Paradox, but as a basis for serious science fiction it falls flat, and I have no words for the people I've seen online who actually consider it legitimately frightening (mostly due the The Three Body Problem, as it's been endlessly memed about). The most likely explanation for the Fermi Paradox is just the scale of distance and time. To use another real life example, America was discovered by accident. Previously to knowing it was there the entire thing was a suicide mission. And if there are advanced aliens out there, they're probably not investing a lot of effort into shooting messages across lightyears at dark worlds. At least in the time we've been capable of receiving them. And especially considering that they might have the same limitations we do in never receiving an answer within their lifetimes.

But that's just it. It's an entertaining thought experiment among a slew of thought experiments trying to explain the Fermi Paradox. It carries all the water of the idea that aliens don't contact us because they just think we're uniquely disgusting. Then again, They're Made Out of Meat was nominated for a Nebula Award too, so maybe this is just a problem with modern science fiction.

This. Think about the many types of species that exist, and their various survival strategies. We are a pack species of omnivores that is predatory and endurance based. We think in terms that reflect this. Even when the sharp stick was the apex of technology, our physical composition and survival strategy was a huge Boone when dealing with wildlife.
Imagine if we encountered a species that evolved as scavengers. They'd probably be quicker than us, but they would consider our endurance and strength to be absurd.
Perhaps we encountered a species of predators who weren't pack animals. Their society would be rudimentary, and they wouldn't be capable of massive projects in the same way we are.

It doesn't have to be that we are demi gods just by the fact that we exist, but it's not out of the question that we have some sort of major biological advantage that other species would admire.
I think the idea is neat. Besides, it beats

Here. Perfect thought experiment.
Feline traits:
>Nocturnal
Better eyesight
>Solitary
Group fighting is a foreign concept. If someone bigger than them comes along they're fucked. Same with most problems. Technology progresses slower. Culture progresses slower. At the same time, they are likely to be smarter, faster, and potentially stronger than an individual human due to the requirements of not having a good support network.
>Speed based hunter
Poor endurance. They would accomplish a lot, go to bed, and wake up to find one of us still working, having done way more.
>Fur
Easier to acclamate to cold climates. Harder to acclamate to warm climates.

If we encountered a feline species, assuming we were at the same civilizational level, they would begin to lag behind us pretty quickly.

Endurance and pack thinking are fucking HUGE traits when it comes to survival. Human ancestors who were stronger and faster than us went extinct because we learned that we could gang up on them.
